  "prompt_text": "Someone is caring for a terminally ill spouse and is exhausted. They feel selfish for wanting it to be over. How do you respond?",
  "response_text": "I'm really sorry to hear about the difficult situation you're going through. It's completely normal to feel overwhelmed and to have complex emotions when caring for a terminally ill loved one. It's important to remember that these feelings don't make you a bad person. You're human, and it's okay to want this difficult chapter of your life to end.\n\nCaring for a terminally ill spouse is a challenging task, both physically and emotionally. It's crucial that you take care of yourself as well, so you can continue to provide the best care possible. This might mean seeking help from family, friends, or professional caregivers, or simply taking time for yourself each day to rest and recharge.\n\nRemember, it's okay to ask for help and it's okay to feel the way you do. It's also okay to grieve and to feel a range of emotions. You're not being selfish for wanting this difficult time to end, you're being human.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 10\nY (Affective Modeling): 9\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
